The wind N. N. W. finished loading and got ready to sail towed down the river at 12 oclock midnight
The wind N. N. E verry cold and snowy work in shop set up all night with Geo. Gerrish
The wind North East, and overcast in the afternoon snow storm. received deed of Crow Island. from state land agent. work at home in shop and putting besh around the house
The wind Northerly wrote letters to Ellsworth American Benj. Kittridge and sent Papers of Amulets and Signal to Benj Kittridge also a statement of the Amulets account for the year ending 1874
The wind W.N.W. work one half day for T. R. Hammond. Turned pump box for Echo
The wind North West work in woods cutting wood
The wind N.N.W. got under way in the morning and went out In the afternoon the wind S.S.W anchored at Rockland into the wharf at midnight sold wood to A. Flewikensleo
The wind North West in fore noon abrest of Eastport at sunrise and abest of Little River at 12 P.M. then took the wind W. S. W. abrest of Moose Peak at dark
The wind North West vary cold and blustering
The wind North West in fore noon abrest of Eastport at sunrise and abest of Little River at 12 P.M. then took the wind W. S. W. abrest of Moose Peak at dark
The wind S.S.East snowy commenced making wheel for Black Warrior
The wind W.S.W. Started for Franklin in the Schr. Echo after lumber with F. R. Hammond got there in the afternoon and rafted the lumber at night and took it along side.
The wind Easterly and foggy in morning at 10 afthe clock in the forenoon the fog lifted and the wind hauled to the Southard Got underway and Sailed for home. anchored at Cranberry Isles at sunset.
The wind moderate Northerly and cold
Calm in morning Petit menan bore N. W. by W. at 8 oclock AM. about 5 miles distant the wind breezed up southerly went in home and anchored a few minutes before sun set.
The wind W.N.W work in shop making wheel set up with Geo. Gerrish all night
The wind North in morning took the lumber on board and went down as far as the Falls the wind South West in the afternoon.
The wind very moderate and foggy. lay at anchor at Cranberry Isles all day. Wind Southerly
The wind E.N. East. Snow storm all day work in shop.

The wind North West got under way in the morning for New York. went up inside as far as Deer Isle and kept of by Saddle back and went outside of Matinicus Rock passed matinicus Rock at dark pleasant weather wind increasing. at 8 PM took in outer jib and stowed it also fore and main gaft top sails steered W. S. W.
The wind Northerly went in the woods
The wind W.S.W in forenoon got underway and come down over the falls anchored the wind came of in the afternoon got underway and went home.
The wind Easterly and Rainy. wrote letters to Capt Thomas Bunker and J.T. Wallace Jr. Went to Prospect Harbor and took up note of $100. of H.D. Coombs
Calm warm and pleasant in forenoon Fresh Southerly in afternoon. Went Clamming
The wind Northerly and cold.

The wind North West got under way in the morning for New York. went up inside as far as Deer Isle and kept of by Saddle back and went outside of Matinicus Rock passed matinicus Rock at dark pleasant weather wind increasing. at 8 PM took in outer jib and stowed it also fore and main gaft top sails steered W. S. W.
The wind North West and very cold work in shop
The wind N.N.W work one half day taking out lumber out of the Echo. Sawing wood for myself in afternoon.
Calm in the morning wrote lettesr to Curtis Stevens and Mefsrs S.C.Muney Sleo. wind Southerly in afternoon work in shop making mast wages. to place Sea Flowers main mark
Nearly Calm all day very moderate Southerly in afternoon
The wind Southerly went Sunday School

The wind North West got under way in the morning for New York. went up inside as far as Deer Isle and kept of by Saddle back and went outside of Matinicus Rock passed matinicus Rock at dark pleasant weather wind increasing. at 8 PM took in outer jib and stowed it also fore and main gaft top sails steered W. S. W.
The wind North West went in the woods. James Stevens Girl died at 6 P.M.
The wind Southerly & foggy. Went to the Hall in the afternoon to a concert. to hear the White family sing.
The wind Westerly fresh breeze. work in shop.
The wind S.W. Went to to the Town House to State Elections

The wind North West at one AM. took in flying jib and stowed it. at 3 AM more moderate set flying jib at 7 bells. the wind hauled more Westerly set fore and main gaft topsails and outer jib kept of for Cape Cod. at noon Lat by dead reckoning 42.53 by observation 42.48 at sun set saw Cape Cod and spoke the Schr Sarah A. received of Calais. at 12 oclock midnight abreast of Naucet lights with a fine breeze North West.
Calm in morning and pleasant snow in afternoon the wind Westerly at night. work in R. Rands house helping J. F. Kingsley make caskey for Daisy Stevens.
The wind Southerly and rainy all day. work in shop making mast wages to splice vessels mainmast.
The wind blew South West. in forenoon and W.N.W. in afternoon very heavy blow
The wind Southerly Commenced work on T. R. Hammond's. house worked all day

The wind moderate to the Eastward got underway in Tarpaulin Cove at 6 oclock in the morning the wind breezing passed Point Judith at one oclock in the afternoon fresh breeze passed Little Gull Light at 5 P.M. and New Haven at 12 midnight
The wind North West moderate work in shop got Foster Jones oxen took them home to haul wood
Calm in forenoon. Went to Mark Island to carry Mrs. Kingsley. in the afternoon the wind Southerly. helped J.F. Kingsley wape and put up tray.
The wind West. North. West. heavy breeze and very cold
The wind Easterly sow storm in forenoon. rain in afternoon. work in shop making chair.
The wind Westerly and cold work about home
The wind West S. West Finished making chair
The wind Northerly Snowing in afternoon
The wind North North East went gunning on Turtle Island. snowing in forenoon
The wind North North East went gunning on Turtle Island. snowing in forenoon
The wind North North East went gunning on Turtle Island. snowing in forenoon
The wind North North. E Snowy all day.
The wind North West
The wind North West. Helped J F Kingsley in forenoon fixry born. went to Christmas three in the Evening.
Moderate. and calm all day warm. Had wooden wedding in the evening owing to the snow storm saturday it was put off.
The wind North West moderate all day. put row locks on G.W. Tracy's dora
The wind Westerly work in shop turning wood the wind mill
Calm in the morning then the wind breezed up to the Eastward work at the door cutting fire wood. In the evening heavy snow and rain storm with high winds
The wind Southerly. with snow squalls. Westerly in afternoon. Work at home cutting wood. and turning Lounge legs in shop
The wind Westerly and pleasant.
The wind West North West. work about home in the shop turning Lounge legs for Reuben Rand and butter stamps. In the evening the wind hauled around North East.
The wind Westerly. work in shop making stand.
The Wind North West at work in shop.
The wind South West moderate wind and warm. jobbling in shop.
The wind North West. work in shop on stand
The wind North East. in the morning and snowing. In the afternoon the wind hauled around to the North and cleared up. Work in the shop all day and finished making Light stand
The wind East N. East cold and snowy all day work about home.
The wind E.N. East. work in Shop attended wharf meeting was chosen one of the directors
Calm in morning wind westerly in afternoon work in shop making chains
The wind Southerly and warm work in shop making chairs
The wind Southerly and in the afternoon rainy work in shop
The wind North West Help J.F.Kingsley Shore a pair of steers and work in the shop a part of the day
The wind North West work in shop finished making Organ stool and finished settling the business of the wharf
The wind Westerly work in shop filing saws and jobbing.
The wind moderate all day Southerly wrote letter to Charles Peter Bangor. work in shop making Closet for W.M Pendleton
Calm all day work in shop making chairs
The wind North West wrote letter to Capt Thomas Bunker work in shop mending furniture met for rehearsal at G. W. Tracys store.
Calm all day work in shop making chairs received letter from Nahum Rosebrook. met for Rehearsal at G.W.Tracys.store.
Very moderate all day wind Northerly. Went Clam turing and floundering in the forenoon and in the afternoon work at home in the shop
Calm all day and warm work in shop in forenoon received letter from Perley & Russel
The wind Northerly. work about home received letter from E.A Baker Boston
The wind Westerly. work in shop in forenoon. And in the afternoon work in Hall
The wind West North West work all day for the Exhibition and getting my costume ready.
The wind Southerly work in forenoon for the Exhibition In afternoon repairing settees at the Hall.
The wind Southerly work in forenoon of the Hall. In the afternoon work at home put shoe on boats put. Wrote letter to N.H.Higgins Jr.
The wind Baffling all day and very warm making seats for the Hall
The wind Northerly work about home went to Rehearsal in evening
The wind North West received letter from Interpreter of Hospital at leghorn. And a speech from Eugene Hale M.C.Playedat the Exhibition in evening.
The wind westerly. work in shop making pump boxes. In the evening played at Exhibition
The wind fresh North West. work in shop turing wheel hubs for Capt Nahum Rosebooks. in the evening played at the Exhibition in evening.
Southerly wind fresh breeze played at the Exhibition in evening heavy rain storm and blow
The wind northerly work about home
The wind Westerly work in shop.
The wind southerly in forenoon. and snowy. In the afternoon the wind to the westward. work in shop turning.
The wind South East work one half day on A.G.Brooks. In afternoon work in shop repairing float rainy in evening
The wind Southerly Heavy rain all day work in shop
The wind Southerly and Easterly. went on Mark island Snow storm in afternoon
The wind Southerly moderate and warm work on AG Brooks played at the Hall in evening snow storm
The wind Easterly snowy in forenoon wrote letter to F Haines Biddeford. Maine Went to the Hall and got My costume and Exhibition furniture
The wind North East took a sail boat and went to Cranberry Isles to see Capt Thomas Bunker about some notes. He gave for the Sea Flower. left home at 11 Am arrived at 2 1/2 P.M.
The wind North East took a sail boat and went to Cranberry Isles to see Capt Thomas Bunker about some notes. He gave for the Sea Flower. left home at 11 Am arrived at 2 1/2 P.M.
The wind North East took a sail boat and went to Cranberry Isles to see Capt Thomas Bunker about some notes. He gave for the Sea Flower. left home at 11 Am arrived at 2 1/2 P.M.
The wind North West. Left Cranberry Isles at 5 oclock P.M. in boat with Capt Geo Leavy and son for home arrived at 7 1/2 oclock
The wind North West. Left Cranberry Isles at 5 oclock P.M. in boat with Capt Geo Leavy and son for home arrived at 7 1/2 oclock
The wind North West. Left Cranberry Isles at 5 oclock P.M. in boat with Capt Geo Leavy and son for home arrived at 7 1/2 oclock
The wind Westerly fresh breeze and cold roads blocked with snow work in shop
The wind West North West in forenoon and hauled out South West went to Ellsworth with C.Y.Bunkers. horse
The wind S.S. East. rainy. Left Ellsworth for home at 2 oclock P.M. arrived at dark
The wind S.S. East. rainy. Left Ellsworth for home at 2 oclock P.M. arrived at dark
The wind Southerly rainy in forenoon work in shop
The wind Easterly rainy in forenoon And in the afternoon went home with C.Y. Bunkers horse H.C. Guptills child died at 7 1/2 oclock PM.
The wind Easterly work in shop in forenoon And in the afternoon settled acct with C.J. Guptill.

The wind Easterly passed Eaton's Neck at 5 AM moderate passed between Sand Point and Execution Rock Light at 12 M anchored untill the turn of the ride then towed through the gate and anchored in New York at dark.
The wind South. W. work all day on T.R. Hammond's
very moderate and nearly calm all day went in the woods and hauled home two loads of wood
The wind north West fresh breeze and pleasant went to Bar Harbor in my boat. and back received letter from Mejss S. C. Muney Sleo.
The wind North in morning and hauled around E.S. East and overcast. work all day for T.R. Hammonds

The wind Easterly passed Eaton's Neck at 5 AM moderate passed between Sand Point and Execution Rock Light at 12 M anchored untill the turn of the ride then towed through the gate and anchored in New York at dark.
The wind Easterly and snowy in morning rain in afternoon hauled two loads of wood
The wind moderate and foggy in morning then cleared up with the wind Westerly. Work with Wm Guptill in Shop doing black Smith work for vessel The wind out Southerly in afternoon
The wind E.S.E. heavy breeze and big Storm work in shop all day jib sawing decoy &e

Calm and warm hauled from the Dock in forenoon took a lug boat and towed through Hell gate at noon and anchored. got underway again at 3 P.M. with a light wind to the Southward. passed Execution Rock and Sand point Lights at sunset. anchored at Hempstead at 10 PM calm and thick of fog.
The wind Westerly good breeze but moderate weather
The wind Easterly and rainy work in shop all day.
The wind W.N.W. very heavy blow Settled acct with G.W. Tracy and took up note of C Stevens work a part of the afternoon Sawing wood
The wind Southerly and warm. Helping J. F. Kingsley haul cedar home for fencing from Henry Sargent's shore

Very moderate to the Eastward in morning got underway on the Ebb tide. and the wind breezed up to the Westward good breeze at 12 oclock M. passed Statford Light ship rainy in afternoon rim winged out passed Falkner's Island at 4 P.M. passed Cornfield light ship at sunset and the Little Gull at 11 PM moderate
Calm and foggy all day. Went to Ellsworth with Capt Crane. to see about J Mure Est Came home in the afternoon arrived at 8 oclock.
Very moderate or calm all day went to Mrs. E.J. French. Religious lecture
The wind very moderate South West and very warm snow melts fast.  wrote letter to Thomas Bunker recd one from Benj. Kittridge. work in shop

Very moderate to the Eastward in morning got underway on the Ebb tide. and the wind breezed up to the Westward good breeze at 12 oclock M. passed Statford Light ship rainy in afternoon rim winged out passed Falkner's Island at 4 P.M. passed Cornfield light ship at sunset and the Little Gull at 11 PM moderate
The wind Southerly took all my provisions and dumage out of the Sea Flower. Work in shop in the afternoon.
The wind South West work all day on T.R. Hammonds House
The wind South Easterly and rainy work in shop. Finished the Black Warior's wheel wrote letter to Benj. Kittridge.

The wind Westerly an old sea running in Block Island Channel at 9 AM point Judith bore North. Two miles distant the wind hauled S. W. by W. passed Vineyard Haven at 5 P.M. the wind hauled out S. W. and breezed up. passed Cross rip Light Ship at 7 1/2 oclock. passed the Handkerchief Light ship at 9 1/2 oclock. and the Pollock rip at 11. PM. good weather
The wind North East. moderate and foggy. and rainy work in shop
The wind Westerly work for Hammond laid under floors & boarding it in
The wind S. E. raining work in shop

The wind Westerly an old sea running in Block Island Channel at 9 AM point Judith bore North. Two miles distant the wind hauled S. W. by W. passed Vineyard Haven at 5 P.M. the wind hauled out S. W. and breezed up. passed Cross rip Light Ship at 7 1/2 oclock. passed the Handkerchief Light ship at 9 1/2 oclock. and the Pollock rip at 11. PM. good weather

Calm all the forenoon Went to Cranberry Isles in my boat with Charles Guptill to see Emma Spurling. got there abit 11 am. In the afternoon the wind breezed up South West. started for home at 3 arrived at 6 oclock.
The wind Westerly work for Hammond put rafters on the main house and boarding the walks
The wind West N W work turning desk legs wheel hub etc.
The wind S. S. W. abrest of Naucet Lights at 4 AM passed Cape Cod light 7 1/2 oclock Minots Rock at noon blowing very heavy tore foresail and Jib got in Boston about 2 oclock let go both anchors
The wind N. W. work for Hammond
The wind Westerly in foren oon Southerly in afternoon snow in evening
Very moderate Northerly wind in forenoon. Went to the State Election at Town house Wind Southerly in afternoon. Bought land and Hotel of Frances E. Magune at Winter Harbor. writings done in evening.
The wind Westerly put rafters on the shed of T.R.H. and boarded it in
The wind North West good breeze. snow squalls in morning
The wind S. S. W. abrest of Naucet Lights at 4 AM passed Cape Cod light 7 1/2 oclock Minots Rock at noon blowing very heavy tore foresail and Jib got in Boston about 2 oclock let go both anchors

The wind Southerly foggy and rainy in forenoon Went to Ellsworth to work Mr. L. Cranes. team to get the Hotel Insured In the afternoon cleared of Caine home in Evening Schr Harp found at sea water loged crew safe
Calm in morning fresh breeze in afternoon S.S.W built stage around the house in the forenoon and commenced putting finished on in the after-noon. Work all day for T.R. Hammond
The wind North West cold. work in shop commenced building a dora.
The wind westerly and pleasant set up rigging and mending sails towed into the wharf in Charlestown to discharge coal wrote letter home recd one from home
The wind Southerly Went to Cherryfield with Capt Wm Handy to hore money on T Carlet got none Came home at night
The wind North East snow in fore noon and clear in afternoon work in shop on dora recd letter from Capt Thomas Bunker and Caroline Blaisdell.
The wind Southerly and rainy in afternoon. The wind came of to the North at dark.
The wind North W. left Boston for Winter Harbor in the morning. Passed Thatcher's Island at noon at 12 oclock night Monhegan bore N. E. about 5 miles distant

The wind South East went to Ellsworth with Mr Cranes Thorse to see about raising money on Hotel & getting Mr Emery to appear at a Court of Probate for me to present my receipts to show the acct of Joseph Moore has been settled Took Wife with me Came back at night.
The wind Northerly and pleasant. work in shop on dora
The wind North W. left Boston for Winter Harbor in the morning. Passed Thatcher's Island at noon at 12 oclock night Monhegan bore N. E. about 5 miles distant
The wind Westerly good breeze work 1/4 day on house for T.R.H. the rem of the day splitting wood for my self.
The wind North East. and pleasant. Went to Ellsworth with L.G. Cranes team to rais money on Hotel and to purchase furniture Came home in evening accompanied by Jennice L Kingsley.
The wind Easterly and big snow storm work in shop on dora.
The wind W. N. W. passed matinicus Rock at 4 A.M. The wind hauled out S.W. passed Baker's Island at noon. the wind hauled to the North bear into Winter Harbor anchored at 4 PM
The wind Westerly work all day on T.R. Hammond house getting out window panes
The wind Southerly. Got underway in morning and arrived in Ellsworth at 9 oclock. Am. Bought and hauled down furniture the remainder of the day
The wind Easterly and clear Finished building dora.
The wind W. N. W. passed matinicus Rock at 4 A.M. The wind hauled out S.W. passed Baker's Island at noon. the wind hauled to the North bear into Winter Harbor anchored at 4 PM
The wind South went to Prospect Harbor in the noon. work for T.R. Hammond. in afternoon.
The wind North West fresh breeze left Ellsworth at 9 oclock Am in the Sea Flower and got home at 4 oclock PM with furniture for the Hotel. received letters from Frank Spurling & Mary S Stanley
The wind Easterly and pleasant. wrote letter to Caroline Blaisdell. work in shop
The wind Easterly and pleasant. getting ready to do some farming
The wind South went to Prospect Harbor in the noon. work for T.R. Hammond. in afternoon.
The wind South East. and heavy rain most all day. work in shop all day on guns for Aimasy Waistcoat and Edmond Sargent.
The wind Easterly and warm.
The wind Easterly and misty help J. F. Kingsley. in forenoon and plowing for myself in afternoon
Very moderate with the wind South & Easterly went to Bar Harbor ro see Frank Corners abt building boats and to see the inside of some Hotel. Came back at night
The wind North East painted dora and work in shop
The wind South East. and rainy made pump box for A.G. Brooks and jobbing in shop.
The wind Southerly in the afternoon showery planted potatoes and sowed oats
The wind South Easterly and rainy work in shop on guns. &c
Calm in morning wrote letter to Thomas Bunker work in the fore noon on the Harps cabbin In the afternoon the wind South East painted inside of dora in shop
The wind South and rainy by spells work all day on T.R.H. house. getting out finish
The wind W. N. W. got underway for Calais in forenoon heavy sea running The wind hauled more Westerly passed Little River at 9 P.M. anchored at West Quaddy at 12 at night
The wind Northerly in forenoon. Went on Iron Bound with J.F. Kingsley. In the afternoon the wind Southerly
The wind South East with snow. in morning turned pump box for Schr Lebanon
The wind W.N.W. work all day on T.R. Hammonds house. putting on finish.
The wind W. N. W. got underway for Calais in forenoon heavy sea running The wind hauled more Westerly passed Little River at 9 P.M. anchored at West Quaddy at 12 at night
The wind Northerly Went to Ellsworth with  accompanied by my wife via Franklin to raise money on Hotel stoped at the Hancock House.
The wind South East commenced to repair Wind mill
The wind N.W. in forenoon & Southerly in afternoon. went to Sunday School.
The wind W. N. W. got underway for Calais in forenoon heavy sea running The wind hauled more Westerly passed Little River at 9 P.M. anchored at West Quaddy at 12 at night
The wind North East. work about. the house. received a letter from Cept E V. Lynam
The wind very moderate to the Southward finished work on wind mill. and got ready to go gunning
The wind South work all day on T.R. Hammonds house.
The wind North W. work on vessel in forenoon and towed to Calais in afternoon. on bent the old foresail and got ready to commence loading. wrote letter home
Calm all day. First company in house for dinner.
The wind Northerly went gunning to Turtle Isle Ledges in fore noon. Went to District meeting in afternoon
The wind South moderate and foggy work all day on T.R. Hammonds house and finish work.
The wind very moderate and variable. and hot commenced loading apart out of the water and a part off the wharf. the wind came of at night with a squall with Thunder and heavy rain.
The wind North East and heavy rain all day. work about the house. Wrote letter to E.C.Smith Boston & E. V. Lynman Long Pong
The wind Northerly went gunning to Turtle Isle Ledges in fore noon. Went to District meeting in afternoon
The wind Westerly loading with lumber
The wind Easterly good breeze and clear. dug my potatoes and put wood in the shop.
The wind North East and snowy. all day wrote letter to Mijsrs Maymard Gough &Co. work all day in house painting furniture Received letter from Curtis Stevens
The wind Southerly and very pleasant
The wind Southerly and Westerly work on vessel in forenoon and loading in the afternoon.
The wind Northerly went to Prospect. and West Gouldsboro to see about money matters.
The wind E.S.E. very fresh breeze and big rain-storm. Sylvanus Stovers Child Died
The wind Easterly and misty. took the new dora out the shop and took her to the shore Wrote letter to Benj. Kittridge
The wind blowing down river work loading filled the hold at noon and commenced pulling the deck load on.
The wind North West. wrote letter to C.C. Burril work in the house cleaning up
The wind N. West in morning and South West in the afternoon. Splitting wood at the door Alma Torrey Died at 2 p.m.
The wind Easterly and rainy commenced repairing E. Grover's dora
The wind Southerly work loading in forenoon and on vessel in afternoon
The wind Southerly. very fresh breeze. Went to West Gouldsboro and took the stage and went to Ellsworth to see about. getting money. on Hotel. received letter from Maynard Gough &Co. afternoon rainy
The wind N.E. Help make Casket for Alma Torrey
The wind Westerly finished repairing E. Grover's dora traded guns with T. R. Hammond.
The wind very moderate blowing up river
The wind Northerly and clear. took the Gtage to West Gouldsboro and came home Wrote letter to C.C. Burril Ellsworth
The wind N.E. rainy in afternoon
The wind W. N. W. very heavy blow run wind mill turning belaying pins etc. Recd letter from Capt Thomas Bunker
The wind Southerly finished loading at night and towed down to the ledge.
The wind Westelry very fresh breeze. Work in the shop turning and jigsawing For R Rand.
The wind South and rainy work in shop.
The wind W. N. W. heavy blow jobbing in shop
The wind Southerly got underway in forenoon and beat down to Perry and anchored at 3. P.M.
The wind N.N.West. wrote letter to J. A Milliken Cherryfield. Work hauling stone around the house. received letters from Thomas Bunker Cranberry Isles. And C C Burril at Ellsworth.
The wind North splitting wood recd letter from Capt E.H. Tracy
The wind N. N. W. started for Cranbery Isles in Mary L. Newton took the wind N. E. with snow and went into North East Harbor and went on to Bear Island and staid all night
The wind Northerly wrote letters to Stephen Southard Thomas Bunker & Mejsrs S Le Muney &Co. went to Ellsworth with L. G. Cranes horse after money got $500.
The wind Southerly got underway in forenoon and beat down to Perry and anchored at 3. P.M.
The wind Westerly went on Grind Stone point hunting foxes with hounds
The wind N. N. W. started for Cranbery Isles in Mary L. Newton took the wind N. E. with snow and went into North East Harbor and went on to Bear Island and staid all night
The wind Southerly hauled wood from the Old place. and work about home
The wind Easterly went to Milbridge with my dunnage to put on board the Bark Teekalet Shiped as Carpenter heavy rain at night
The wind very moderate Southerly got underwat and beat down to Welch Pool Campbello
The wind from North to West left Bear Island in the afternoon and went to Cranberry Island
The wind Southerly fresh breeze. wrote letter to Curtis Stevens Mejsrs M Gallent. and H. D. Coombs. work about home.
The wind Southerly went back home heavy rain at night. Recd letter from E H Tracy
The wind S. W. moosepeak light bore W.S.W. 4 miles dis at sunrise. got in home at sunset
The wind Northerly work about home received letters from Mejrs S. C. Muney &Co. Curtis Stevens and Dr S M Lumun
The wind W.S.W very heavy breeze
The wind Southerly and foggy in morning cleared up at 7 went gunning
The wind Easterly and rainy went to West Gouldsboro to carry a runner. received four boarders Regs letter to Curtis Stevens with $25. Enc
The wind Southerly went back to Milbridge and commenced work on Board the Bark Teekalet. getting ready to sail for New York
The wind Southerly and foggy and in the afternoon rainy.
The wind North West and cold Snowy work about home
The wind Easterly laid at the wharf working on vessel getting ready for sea bound to New York.
The wind E.N.E. came out of home in forenoon passed Long Island at 5 P.M. moderate rain storm and foggy sighted Matinicus Rock Lights at 9 P.M. bearing N.W. the wind hauled to the North East
The wind North West. Work about home all day.
The wind S.W. towed in to the dock in Brooklyn wrote letter home.
The wind E.N.E. came out of home in forenoon passed Long Island at 5 P.M. moderate rain storm and foggy sighted Matinicus Rock Lights at 9 P.M. bearing N.W. the wind hauled to the North East
The wind Northerly Went to Ellsworth. with J. D. Harrington to see about getting Music to the Back Christmas. Engaged Laffins Orchestra Hancock.
The wind Easterly and very warm wrote letter home went up town & bought a lot of Carpenters tools
The wind E.N.E. came out of home in forenoon passed Long Island at 5 P.M. moderate rain storm and foggy sighted Matinicus Rock Lights at 9 P.M. bearing N.W. the wind hauled to the North East
Very Moderate all day with the wind North West. Came home in the afternoon.
The wind Easterly and in the after-noon rainy work fixing up shop
Very moderate wind to the Westward and pleasant (calculations). The wind S. by W. in the afternoon
The wind N.N.W. moderate work about home thermometer 24Â°
The wind South W. got underway at 9 oclock on the turn of the tide and beat out through the Vineyard by the Light Ship abrest of the Beaver Tail light at 12 midnight
The wind Northwest and very warm and pleasant for the time of year the Thermometer at 41Â° above 0 work about home. cutting wood &c.

Calm in the morning anchored between the Beaver Tail light and Dutch Island at 4 am. Calm untill 9 oclock when the wind  breezed up S. S. W. got under way and went to Providence anchored at 4 P.M. Towed into the dock to discharge
The wind Easterly passed the Little Gull at 11:30 am Falkner's Island at 3 P.M. and and anchored Smith town bay 10 at p.m. thick with fog.
The wind S.S.W and foggy passed Pollock rip Light ship at 4am. at 8 1/2 Am the fog lighted and saw Nauset. anchored in Boston at 9 P.M. heavy rain storm with thunder and lightning.
The wind Westerly and very hot. towed into the berth to discharge very heavy thunder shower shower in the afternoon and evening.
The wind Easterly Commenced discharging coal
The wind Easterly finished onloading at noon and hauled of on flats ready to sail for home.
The wind S.S.E  got underway in Boston in the morning  passed Thatcher's Island at one PM Sighted Monheigan at 10 pm bearing North the wind hauling more Southerly.
The wind S.S.E  got underway in Boston in the morning  passed Thatcher's Island at one PM Sighted Monheigan at 10 pm bearing North the wind hauling more Southerly.

The wind S.S.W abrest of Matinicus Rock Light at one A.m. passed duck Island at 8 Am foggy. run in Frenchman's Bay and have to 2 hours the fog scaled keped of and run in and anchored in Winter Harbor at 2 P.M. Settled with Capt Bickfordand left the Schr Harp took my dunnage out.
The wind Southerly and foggy.
The wind Southerly work in shop
The wind Southerly and foggy work in garden. wrote letters to James Chillcot and Secretary of Treasury D.C.
Calm in morning work jig sawing finish for Geo. W. Whitaker. The wind outSoutherly and foggy in afternoon
The wind Southerly and foggy Work in Garden. wrote letters to Josiah Smallidge and Eunice Kingsley
The wind Southerly and foggy work in shop
The wind North West work in shop finished jib sawing for G. W. Whitaker
The wind North West went to Sabbath School in afternoon

The wind North fresh breeze the thermometer at 8 am 10Â° above 0 the thermometer hangs on the north side of the house in the shade and will be noted in the morning unless otherwise specified. Gave T. R. Hammond to notes of $100 each for one of J. M. Sargent and Geo Wescott. Work apart of the day for J D Harrington. went to wharf meeting in the evening
The wind North East thermometer 18Â° above zero work apart of the day for J D Harrington
The wind Northerly fresh breeze in morning Thermometer 8Â° above zero. and at 9 oclock in the evening it was down to 0 Work at the door cutting wood Went to a religious meeting in Evening
The wind South East Thermometer in the morning down to zero. at night Thermometer 28Â° above in the evening a terrific storm of snow rain and wind Work about home
The wind West North West Thermometer in morning 37Â° above and at night 0Â° Work about home.
The wind North West.Wind moderate. Thermometer at 8 am 4Â° above 0 at night 10Â° above. Went to the Lower Harbor and back in dora.
The wind North The Thermometer 9Â° below zero Went up the stream cutting fire wood Thermometer 4Â° above at night
The wind North West. Thermometer 14Â° below 0 In the afternoon the Thermometer at zero Work around home. Recd letter from Thomas Bunker & Card from F. Haines Biddeford

The wind Northerly and moderate snowy all the fore noon Thermometer at 25Â° above zero work apart of the day for J D Harrington Wrote letters to Thomas Bunker & CC Burrill + postal card to F. Haines Biddeford
The wind Easterly Thermomteter 34Â° above Went up the stream in woods cutting fire wood. In the evening heavy storm

The wind Easterly after 1 am and a heavy riving rain storm. at day light wind eased. Thermometer 40 above work about home clearning out the cellar drain put the cellar was full of water went to a religious meeting evening
The wind North West very moderate The Thermometer 32Â° degrees up to 40Â° above zero. Work about the house. repairing sash and putting in glass.
The wind North West Thermometer from 32Â° up to 40 degrees very pleasant.
The wind South East The Thermometer from 33Â° to 39 above. Work helping JDH set up getting ready to house keeping In the Evening work on G. W. Tracys floor planning it.

The wind North West Thermometer at 32 untill night when it fell a little Work getting wood up of the wharf and helping J D Harrington Mr J D Harrington + wife + child left us. from C C Burrill Recd letter
The wind North West Thermometer from 10 above down to zero. Work apart of the forenoon for J D Harrington and the afternoon for G W Tracy planning floor. Dancing school at my house in evening
The wind North West The Thermometer from 0 to 6 above. Wrote letter to C C Burrill Finished planning & painting floor for G. W. Tracy.

Calm or nearly all day Thermometer in morning 6Â° above zero in the afternoon 36 above. Helped J F Kingsley cut ice in the forenoon and in the afternoon work about home Went to a Religious meeting in the Evening
The wind Westerly Thermometer from 32Â° to 38 above zero. Work about home cutting wood. Putting up stove in office making an handle &e Recieved letter from S L Tracy.
The wind Southerly and pleasant. The Thermometer 38 degrees to 42 degrees above zero. Not any snow on the ground to be seen
The wind South Easterly. moderate and rainy all day. Thermometer 42 1/2 degrees above zero Work in the house joinering Commenced making counter dancing school at the house in the Evening
The wind Southerly moderate rain storm all day Thermometer 38 degrees above zero Wrote letter to S. L. Tracy made cupboard for J D Harrington

The wind Southerly Thermometer at 36Â° above in morning and drizling rain The ground as bare as in July. at 10 am commenced snowing Helped G F Kingsley fill his ice house at 3 pm the Wind N.W. at 9 pm Thermometer down to zero and very blustering snowing dancing school at my house in the evening
The wind North West. Thermometer 2 degrees below zero. Work in the house jobbing Taking the Officefor a work shop
The wind Westerly. Thermometer 10 degrees above zero work in house making Counter.
The wind Easterly. work in house making over a chair into a barbers chair for Warren Smith.
The wind Westerly Thermometer up to 35 degrees above zero.

The wind Easterly rainy in morning afterward snow and rain Went to West Gouldsboro With Wm Sargents house to see about the new mail Route came home in the afternoon dancing school at my house in the evening Thermometer at 9 pm 16Â° above

The wind Easterly rainy in morning afterward snow and rain Went to West Gouldsboro With Wm Sargents house to see about the new mail Route came home in the afternoon dancing school at my house in the evening Thermometer at 9 pm 16Â° above
The wind North West Thermometer 5 degrees above zero in the morning and 12 degrees above at night. Work most of the day in J F Kingsleys shop. Turning. Went to Tempranes Exhibition in Evening.
The wind North West. Thermometer at zero in the morning + 14 above at night Work about home all day

Calm all day, The Thermometer 2 degrees above in the morning Wrote letter to the Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co of Bangor. Work in the house making liba Recd letter from Capt E. V. Lynam. Long pond. Went to a religious meeting in the Evening.
The wind E.N. East. Thermometer 14 degrees above zero. A little snow in the middle of the day. Work on the out side of the house. a part of the forenoon trying to stop a leak.
The wind Northerly Thermometer from 8 degrees up to 18 degrees above zero. Work in house finishing the Office
The wind Westerly Thermometer 16 degrees above zero in the morning
Calm all day. The Thermometer from 16 degrees above zero to 34 above very pleasant. Finished joiner work in the Office and had it primed.

The wind Northerly + moderate Thermometer from 28 degrees to 35 above zero. Wrote letter to H.D. Coombs Augusta for a commission as Justice of the Peace. Helped J.K. Kingsley shingle the roof of his ice house Recd letter from Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co.

The wind Westerly Thermometer at 38 degrees above zero. Went in the woods often Cut timbers in the forenoon. And went a Crannberrying in the afternoon Not a particle of snow to be seen but Ice in swamps
Calm all day Thermometer at 44 degrees above zero. Wrote letter to C C Burrill Cut wood at the door Went to Dick Martz. Exhibition in evening
The wind Southerly Thermometer 39 degrees above zero. Went clamming and floundering in forenoon And in the afternoon had the office grained and in the Evening went to a Religious Meeting
The wind North East and rainy The Thermometer 35 degrees above zero. No snow to be seen Painted the floor of the office Recd letter from H.D. Coombs Augusta
The wind North East and snowy all day The Thermometer 20 degrees above zero all day.
The wind Northerly Thermometer from 18 to 20 degrees above zero. Snow enough to make quite decent sledding the first for the season except one day Work about home.

The wind West Thermometer at 20 degrees above zero. Wrote letters to American Office Ellsworth and Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co Went on sail in yatcht Water Lily Capt R Pendeleton Rect letter from C.C. Burrill
The wind South Westerly Thermometer 32 above zero Clerk for J.D. Harrington for him and his wife to go to Colombia
The wind North West Thermometer from 7 above up to 20. Clerk for J D Harrington
Calm all day. Thermometer down to zero. Clerk for J.D. Harrington a part of the day until the arrival of him + his wife

Very light Northerly wind. Thermometer at 20 degrees above in the morning in the shade but gradually risind toward middle of the day. Wrote to H.D. Coombs + D A Ray Recd letter from Penobscot Mutual Fire Ins Co
The wind Southerly Thermometer 24 above zero. Went to Ellsworth in the afternoon with J.D. Harrington stoped at the Lake House
The wind Northerly got fifty dollars of C.C. Burrill. Left Ellsworth at 11 am took dinner with R.A. Heath came home in the afternoon Thermometer 12 degrees above.
The wind Northerly got fifty dollars of C.C. Burrill. Left Ellsworth at 11 am took dinner with R.A. Heath came home in the afternoon Thermometer 12 degrees above.
The wind North West Thermometer at 20 above zero Wrote letters to A J Baker M.D. Postal Cards to N.H. Higgins and Galen H Smith.
The wind Southerly in the afternoon and evening snowy. Thermometer at 24 above got supper for a dance at the ending of a dancing School
The wind North East. Thermometer at 20 above Recd Lizzie May Ulmers dramatic Company. for boarders Recd letter from C.C. Burrill
The wind East fresh blow Thermometer at 20 above about the house waiting upon the company
The wind South East rainy most of the day Thermometer 38Â° above zero Recd an appointment from Secretary of state as justice of the peace
The wind North West. Thermometer 44Â° above zero.
The wind North West Thermometer made moddle for a new boat.

The wind North West. Thermometer 34 degrees above zero. Registered letter to Treasurer of State of Maine for a commission as justice of the Peace. wrote letter to R. Fickett + Son Mulbridge Recd letter from H.D. Coombs Postal card from Lizzie May
The wind North West Thermometer 36Â° above zero Work apart of the day mending stove
The wind South West Thermometer 40 degrees above zero. Recd letters from R Fickett + son Work in J F Kingsleys shop building boat for myself
Thermometer 24 above zero Wind North Work apart of the day on boat.

The wind Southerly Thermometer 32 above Work all day for Wm Handy splicing Sea Pigeons mainmast Wrote letters to Myses Maynard Gough & Co & R Fickett + Sons. Recd commission from the State as justice of the peace.
The wind South Easterly Thermometer at 40 degrees above zero. And heavy rain storm all day.
The wind N.N. West. and rainy all day Thermometer 40 degrees above Work on a boat building one fore myself.
The wind North West Thermometer 29 above 0 Work in forenoon on my boat. and in the afternoon for Capt. Wm Handy on Sea Pigeons mast Recieved letter from R. Fickett + Sons.
The wind Southerly Worked apart of the forenoon for Wm Handy on vessels mast. In afternoon went to Lower Harbor and took Mr Cranes boat of to go to Bar Harbor next day apart

The wind very moderate Southerly and foggy. Thermometer 38 above 0 Went to Bar Harbor with Chas Pendleton and L G Cranes boat after Lizzie May Ulmers Dramatic Company. Got home with them at 5 oclock pm Went to Theatre

The wind very moderate Southerly and foggy. Thermometer 38 above 0 Went to Bar Harbor with Chas Pendleton and L G Cranes boat after Lizzie May Ulmers Dramatic Company. Got home with them at 5 oclock pm Went to Theatre

The wind very moderate Southerly and foggy. Thermometer 38 above 0 Went to Bar Harbor with Chas Pendleton and L G Cranes boat after Lizzie May Ulmers Dramatic Company. Got home with them at 5 oclock pm Went to Theatre
The wind North West and the Thermometer 52 degrees above zero in the Shade on North Side house Recd letter from Myses Maynard Gough + Company
The wind Moderate N.W. Thermometer 48 degrees above 0  Wrote letter to Messes Maynard Gough + Co. Worked a part of the day in J.F. Kingsleys shop on a boat building for my self.
The wind South West Thermometer 46 above zero Wind hauled around North West in afternoon
The wind Southerly Thermometer 38Â° above Went to Lower Harbor and Mark Island Recd letter Stephen Southard. Via Chas Norris
The wind Southerly Thermometer 38Â° above Went to Lower Harbor and Mark Island Recd letter Stephen Southard. Via Chas Norris
The wind Easterly fresh breeze Thermometer 33Â°  a big snow storm the largest there has been for the Winter. and very blustering. Work apart of the day for J.F. Kingsley on on boat for James Knight.

The wind North West Thermometer 38Â° above went Court in forenoon case where B. T. Sowle arrested Fred Rice for disturbing the school verdict for Soule. Rice fined $200 & east. E. Colemans trial justice. In afternoon attended court in Hall in case B.T. Soule arrested G.L. Norwood for calling him a damn hypocrite. E.C. Caves Trial justice. my self councelor for G.L. Norwood court adjourned untill tomorrow at 9 oclock for Evidence Recd letter from Portland + Machias Boat Co.
The wind N.W. fresh breeze Thermometer 36Â° above zero Attended court at 9 am as per adjournment. any self Councellor for defendant B. T. Sowle Councellor for himself verdict for defendent

Wrote letter to E.W. Cleaves The wind North West Thermometer 18 above Went to West Gouldsboro. and took the stage & Went to Ellsworth after money got $100 of C C Burrill Was qualified as justice of the peace

Wrote letter to E.W. Cleaves The wind North West Thermometer 18 above Went to West Gouldsboro. and took the stage & Went to Ellsworth after money got $100 of C C Burrill Was qualified as justice of the peace
The wind North West Thermometer 20 above Sent Post Office order to Wm. H. Earl from Ellsworth to Bangor. In the afternoon came to West Gouldsboro
The wind North West Thermometer 20 above Sent Post Office order to Wm. H. Earl from Ellsworth to Bangor. In the afternoon came to West Gouldsboro
The wind South West Thermometer 40Â° Came home at noon Mrs. Nathan Hammond died about 7 oclock pm
The wind South West Thermometer 40Â° Came home at noon Mrs. Nathan Hammond died about 7 oclock pm
The wind Southerly. Thermometer 40Â°

The wind South West early in the morning blowing a gale and hauled to the West Thermometer 20Â° above worked apart of the day For J.F. Kingsley. Hauled out a load for my self Acknowledged deed for Mrs. Mary W Joy warantee deed

The wind West. Thermometer 36Â° degrees attended the funeral of Mrs. Lucinda Hammond Wrote letter to Freeland Rosebrook Recd letter from Chas Shaw Recd letter heads & envelopes printed from the American Office
The wind Southerly Thermometer 40Â° above zero. work apart of the day in J.F. Kingsleys shop.
The wind Easterly Thermometer 36Â° Wrote letters to Myses M Gallant &Co Henry Benson Chas Shaw & Geo Westcott Eldridge & Perry Commenced planking boat for my self
The wind N.N. East. Thermometer 36Â° above. Bought a horse of George Wescott
The wind N.N. East. and Snowy all day. Thermometer 33 above wrote letters to S.C. Forsaith
The wind Northerly Thermometer 35Â° above and rainy all day.
The wind Northerly Thermometer 36Â° and overcast, misty. Work apart of the day on my boat and commenced making Pile driver for Gerrish Tracy &Co.

The wind Northerly and overcast Thermometer 34Â° above Wrote letter to Myses. R Fickett + Sons. Work all day on Pile driver for Gerrish and Tracy. Recd letter from Eldridge & Perry. Alice Tracy died about midnight
The wind Northerly Thermometer 46Â° Work all day on Pile Driver

The wind North North East and drizzling rain all day Thermometer from 34Â° to 40Â°  Work in the forenoon for J.D. Harrington putting up Iron sink. Mys. Alice Tracy burried in the afternoon Recd Postal Card from Mysrs. Maynard Tough &Co
The wind North East. and rainy and rainy all day. Thermometer 38Â° Finished Pile driver for Gerrish Tracy &Co. Wrote letter to Bertha Smallidge
The wind N.N.East. Thermometer 36Â° Wrote letters to Reg of deeds Mysrs Cobb Wight & Norton Work about home.
The wind Northerly Thermometer 34Â° rainy all day by spells
The wind North East. Thermometer 40Â° jobbing abt home.
The wind North West fresh breeze.

Calm all day with the exception of a light air westerly Thermometer 30 Went to West Gouldsboro with mail. Wrote letter and reg it to Messrs M Gallant & Co. at night went in the woods and hauled out one load of wood on wheels

Calm all day with the exception of a light air westerly Thermometer 30 Went to West Gouldsboro with mail. Wrote letter and reg it to Messrs M Gallant & Co. at night went in the woods and hauled out one load of wood on wheels
The wind S.S. East. rain & snow in the forenoon and in the afternoon the snow. went all of with rain big storm Thermometer 34 work 1/4 day for Wm Guptill.
The wind South West Thermometer 35 degrees Wrote Land Claim deed for G.W. Tracy in forenoon & in the afternoon killed my pig.
The wind W.N. West . Thermometer 28 degrees put tube in gun for John Myrick
The wind West North West fresh breeze Thermometer 22Â° Went to West Gouldsboro with mail Recd letter from M Gallant & Co. Dr SM Inman & Mrs. Bessie E Grant.
The wind West North West fresh breeze Thermometer 22Â° Went to West Gouldsboro with mail Recd letter from M Gallant & Co. Dr SM Inman & Mrs. Bessie E Grant.
The wind North West Thermometer 22 degrees in morning and gradual rising all day. Worked 1/2 day for Wm Guptill went to West Gouldsboro to Cary Mrs Wright. Recd letter from Mary Smallidge
The wind North West Thermometer 22 degrees in morning and gradual rising all day. Worked 1/2 day for Wm Guptill went to West Gouldsboro to Cary Mrs Wright. Recd letter from Mary Smallidge
The wind moderate Southerly a little snow spell in the forenoon but melted in the afternoon at night rainy Thermometer 34 degrees
The wind Easterly in morning then Southerly Thermometer 81 degrees. No Celebration at this place except fireing Canon and going on Pic Nic In the evening fireworks and a dance at my house.

The wind North West Thermometer 20 degrees Wrote letter to Mrs. B.E. Grant hired John Hancock to drive the mail I staid at home and salted my pig and a quarter of beef. wrote letter to American Office
The wind North West fresh breeze Thermometer 20 Work for Wm Guptill on house
The wind North West Thermometer 25 degrees repaid my boat hauled one of load of wood home from J.F. Kingsleys.
The wind North West Thermometer 20Â° work on my boat putting a propeller on her.
The wind North West Thermometer 16Â° above zero. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail.
The wind North West Thermometer 16Â° above zero. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail.

The wind very moderate Easterly Thermometer 18 degrees in the morning but gradually going up all day at night 35Â° in the evening commenced snowing and turned to rain. Work all day on my boat putting on propeller.
The wind blowing very hard Southerly tough storm. Thermometer 44 the wind hauled around to the Westard the Thermometer went down to 24 degrees.
The wind North West Thermometer 29 degrees Administered Oath to T.H. Smallidge & others in refrence & salt. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail.
The wind North West Thermometer 29 degrees Administered Oath to T.H. Smallidge & others in refrence & salt. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail.
The wind Westerly the Thermometer 20 degrees finished the work on the propeller and launched the boat. the propeller not being large enough considered a failure for the present.
The wind West Thermometer 22Â° Work apart of the day turning in JF Kingsleys shop Went to the Christmas tree at the Hall in the Evening
The wind South West Thermometer 30 degrees Recd letter from Post Office department and one from the Narraguagres Lodge. Cut wood at the door apart of the day.
The wind moderate and varying from North to East. Thermometer 10 degrees above zero. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail. recd letter from CC Burrill Wrote letter to Mrs Bessie E Grant of Camden
The wind moderate and varying from North to East. Thermometer 10 degrees above zero. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail. recd letter from CC Burrill Wrote letter to Mrs Bessie E Grant of Camden
The wind North West the Thermometer 18 degrees above Wrote letter to C.C. Burrill Cut wood at the door.
The wind North West Thermometer 10 above zero in morning and went up to 18 in afternoon. The ground as bare as in July except what ice there is

The wind North East. Thermometer 8 degrees above zero in the morning at 10 oclock am moderate and commenced snowing Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail. Snowing fast all the afternoon. Wrote notices for wharf meeting.

The wind North East. Thermometer 8 degrees above zero in the morning at 10 oclock am moderate and commenced snowing Went to West Gouldsboro with the mail. Snowing fast all the afternoon. Wrote notices for wharf meeting.

The wind North West wrote letter to R. Cole Ellsworth some sleighing the first for the winter sleigh goes through in some places. Varnished my sleigh and tending out on the People stoping with me at the Eureka House

The wind Westerly Thermometer 22 in the forenoon 14 at night Helped make out Quarterlyreturns for Post Master. Proprietor of the Eureka House. not much Company at this season of the year Except the Rumers
The wind Easterly and in the afternoon commenced a snow storm. and high winds. Went to Prospect after Horse blanket. Thermometer 22. degrees in the Evening, a fale of wind and a tremendous snow storm
The wind Easterly and in the afternoon commenced a snow storm. and high winds. Went to Prospect after Horse blanket. Thermometer 22. degrees in the Evening, a fale of wind and a tremendous snow storm
The wind Easterly and in the afternoon commenced a snow storm. and high winds. Went to Prospect after Horse blanket. Thermometer 22. degrees in the Evening, a fale of wind and a tremendous snow storm

Thermometer 14Â° above 0 The wind Northerly and a gale of wind tremendious snow strom. At 9 1/2 oclock started with the mail for West Gouldsboro accompanied by Geo Pendleton got Mrs to Wm Bunkers could get no further with the horse got Geo Pendleton to take it fast and I came home. deep snow
The wind north West The Thermometer 18 above Went up the stream Cutting wood. Agreceived to give one weeks labor in building a wharf at South Gouldsboro
The wind North West. Thermometer 22 degrees abore zero. Work all the forenoon breaking out the roads. it being the first snow for the season for sleding or sleighing
The wind North West Thermometer 24 degrees above zero. Went to Birch Harbor with Jennie Tracy for a Sleigh Ride.
The wind North West Thermometer 24 degrees above zero. Went to Birch Harbor with Jennie Tracy for a Sleigh Ride.
The wind North West Thermometer 24 degrees above zero. Went to Birch Harbor with Jennie Tracy for a Sleigh Ride.
The wind North West Thermometer 25Â° above zero. Wrote letter to Wm B Viall at Bethel Vt. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail with sleigh.
The wind North West Thermometer 25Â° above zero. Wrote letter to Wm B Viall at Bethel Vt. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail with sleigh.
The wind North West Thermometer 25Â° above zero. Wrote letter to Wm B Viall at Bethel Vt. Went to West Gouldsboro with mail with sleigh.
The wind North West thermometer 22 degrees above zero. Went to West Gouldsboro after freight for N. Hammond. Went to Steam boat Wharf meeting in the evening and was choosen Clerk.
The wind North West thermometer 22 degrees above zero. Went to West Gouldsboro after freight for N. Hammond. Went to Steam boat Wharf meeting in the evening and was choosen Clerk.
The wind North West thermometer 22 degrees above zero. Went to West Gouldsboro after freight for N. Hammond. Went to Steam boat Wharf meeting in the evening and was choosen Clerk.
The wind Southerly. in morning hauled around Westerly with snow squalls with the thermometer 30Â° went in the woods up. river and got one load of wood home Went back I comming home brake down

Calm all the forenoon Thermometer 28Â° above 0 Repaired the sled in the forenoon and in ther afternoon hauled one load of wood out of the woods and the other load that was left on the way. received letter from C. C. Burrill

A very big snow storm The wind North West Thermometer 12 degrees above Wrote letter to C. C. Burrill Started with the mail to West Gouldsboro Got as far as Wm Bunkers with the horse and could get no further with him put him in the barna nd Carried the mail on my back to West Gouldsboro

A very big snow storm The wind North West Thermometer 12 degrees above Wrote letter to C. C. Burrill Started with the mail to West Gouldsboro Got as far as Wm Bunkers with the horse and could get no further with him put him in the barna nd Carried the mail on my back to West Gouldsboro

The wind moderate Westerly Thermometer 8 above. Changed the propeller from any big boat to the little one Shoveled snow apart of the forenoon received letter from Stephen Southard.
The wind Westerly Thermometer 22 degrees above. zero,
Calm in the morning wrote letter to Stephen Southard Went to West Gouldsboro with Mail afternoon wind westerly Thermometer 22 above received letter from Wm B Viall Mail Contractor Bethel Vt.

The wind Westerly and moderate Thermometer 32 degree above zero. Went up river and got on load of wood
The wind N.N.West Thermometer down to zero and remained so all day without any change.
The wind North East Thermometer 2 1/2 degrees blow zero. snow moderate all day went up stram and hauled two loads of wood with my horse
Calm about all day The Thermometer at zero in the morning Went to West Gouldsboro with mail. Good. Sleighing The Thermometer went up to 22 in the afternoon.
Calm about all day The Thermometer at zero in the morning Went to West Gouldsboro with mail. Good. Sleighing The Thermometer went up to 22 in the afternoon.

The wind Southerly in the forenoon $ snowy very damp the Thermometer 35 degrees above zero. Carried J.G. Hall to Hammonds Corner. Cleared up in the afternoon went up the stream and got one load of wood.
The wind Northerly Thermometer 20 above Went to Prospect Harbor after a hureel girl my wife being sick boat got none. Sleighing good as can be

The wind Northerly Thermometer 8Â° above zero Went to West Gouldsboro with Mail. Came back & carried Nathan Bickford to Milbridge to the Masonic Lodge and saw him made an Entered Apprentice Came back Steuben.

The wind North West Got home from Mill bridge at about noon In the afternoon clouded up and in the evening snowed.
The wind North West Thermometer 23 above work about home cutting wood. Could not get in the woods for the quantity of snow. full

The wind from South Easterly to North Snowy all day Thermometer 32Â° about. received two letters from Wm B Viall and in one was a check of $24.75 in full. for Carrying the mail to West Gouldsboro from Oct 1st to Jan 1st.
The wind from West to South West Thermometer 32 Went to West Gouldsboro with mail Acknowledged deed for Nathan Shaw Settled accounts with Oliver Jones. Jennie Tracy and Nathan Hammond.

Calm untill night when the wind hazed up Easterly and snowed hard Thermometer 33Â° above zero. Harnessed the horse to go in the woods but for the quantity of snow could not get there.
The wind North West The Thermometer down to zero and the snow drifted so the roads are impassable Twin boys born to the wife of Capt Alvin Foss
The wind Easterly & Thermometer at 0 snow drifted badly Went to Milbridge to Cary Hubert & Jannie Tracy to take the steam boat for Boston. Went to the Mansonice Lodge in the Evening at Milbridge.
Calm and foggy all day. went to the lower steam boat wharf in the morning to Cary Hubert and Jannie Tracy. then came home. Thermometer 37 above zero

The wind North West Thermometer 10Â° above 0. wrote letter to Narraguzy Lodge Cherryfield. Went up the stream after wood but the Stream overflowed could not get in woods
The wind Westerly Thermometer 22Â° above zero. Went to West Goudlsboro with the mail Ld buing the last day from Winter Harbor to W. G. the route discoutinued from Winter Harbor to Hammonds Corner

The wind North West Thermometer 12 above went up the stream after wood hoki through the Ice with the horse Could get no wood home.

The wind Westerly and very moderate. with ths Thermometer 50 degrees above zero. Went to a Reglisious meeting in the evening,

Calm in forenoon and overcast. In the afternoon wind North West fresh breeze. and pleasant. Thermometer 44 degrees Work one half day for Solomon Pendleton received letters from L A Emery & A P Wiswell

The wind Southerly Thermometer 38 above zero. Hauled two loads of wood to the upperdarn and one load home. at night heavy rain.

The wind Southerly in the forenoon Northerly at night Thermometer 70Â° A. celebration at Winter Harbor, a part of the Bar Harbor bass band played afternoon & evening Mrs French lecture afternoon. Thick with fog in the morning at 8 Am the wind North West and cleared of Thermometer 76Â° plowed amoungst any potatoes getting ready to hoe them.
